// TEST: exec_py_stmt_match_no_early_return
// EXPECT: output "A;B;C;done"
// EXPECT: targets python
//
// A statement-position `match` — one sitting mid-block as a side-effecting
// statement, not the function/value tail nor a value-binding RHS — whose arms
// are *bare expression* bodies (`print(...)`) must NOT abort the enclosing
// function. The Python backend's shared `emit_block_body` lowered a match arm's
// tail expression as a function-body `return`, so a statement match emitted
// `case _BockOk(m): return print(...)` — the `return` aborts the function after
// the matched arm runs. In the chat-protocol example this truncated `main`:
// `match decoded { Ok(m) => println(..) … }` returned out of `main` after the
// first arm, so every section after the decode round-trip was skipped (the run
// still exited 0, hiding it from an exit-code-only view).
//
// The py fix sets a statement-position discard flag (`in_stmt_match_arm`) around
// a statement match's arm emission, so each bare-expression arm body lowers to a
// bare statement (`print(...)`), not `return print(...)`. Two consecutive
// statement matches with print arms plus the trailing `print("done")` pin the
// fall-through: the full line prints only if control flows past BOTH matches.
//
// PYTHON-ONLY: this pins the Python statement-match lowering specifically; the
// other backends already fall through correctly (the spurious `return` lived in
// py.rs alone). A `py_*` fixture name keeps it from claiming cross-backend
// coverage it does not assert. Sibling of py_loop_tail_println_all_iterations,
// which pins the same `emit_block_body` truncation for loop-body tails.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

enum Tag {
  First
  Second
}

fn report(t: Tag) -> Void {
  match t {
    First => print("A;")
    Second => print("Z;")
  }
  print("B;")
  match t {
    First => print("C;")
    Second => print("Z;")
  }
  print("done")
}

fn main() -> Void {
  report(First)
}
